.TH CS 1 "2026-03-20" "cs 1.0.0" "Claude Session Manager"
.SH NAME
cs \- manage Claude Code sessions across multiple hosts
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B cs
.RI [ command ]
.RI [ options ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B cs
aggregates Claude Code session metadata from multiple Linux hosts into a
central MongoDB database, enabling cross-machine session visibility, tagging,
persistent tmux-backed sessions, and remote attach.
.PP
Sessions launched via
.B cs launch
run inside detached tmux sessions that survive SSH disconnects. Session state
(WORKING, WAITING, IDLE, DEAD) is detected from tmux pane content. Any session
can be reconnected from any machine via
.BR "cs attach" ,
which automatically SSH's to the remote host when necessary.
.PP
Running
.B cs
with no arguments displays a smart dashboard showing active sessions, recent
activity, and sessions needing attention.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B cs
Display the local dashboard. Shows a single merged table of this machine's
sessions with live tmux state overlaid on database records. No duplicates.
Falls back to tmux-only display if MongoDB is unreachable.
.TP
.BI "cs sync" " [--quiet]"
Harvest session metadata from
.I ~/.claude/projects/
and upsert to MongoDB. Detects active tmux sessions and their state. With
.BR --quiet ,
suppresses all output (suitable for
.I .bashrc
login hooks).
.TP
.BI "cs list" " [--local] [--host name] [--project name] [--limit n]"
List sessions from the database sorted by most recently updated. Defaults to
all hosts. Options:
.RS
.TP
.B --local
Show sessions from this host only.
.TP
.BI --host " name"
Filter to a specific host. Accepts short names (e.g.,
.I dev
matches
.IR dev.example.com ).
.TP
.BI --project " name"
Filter by project name.
.TP
.BI --limit " n"
Maximum number of results (default: 20).
.RE
.TP
.BI "cs launch" " project [prompt]"
Start Claude Code in a detached tmux session.
The session persists across SSH disconnects. If
.I prompt
is provided, it is passed to Claude as the initial message.
.TP
.BI "cs adopt" " id-or-name [--attach]"
Wrap an existing Claude session in a managed tmux session. The session is
resumed via
.B claude --resume
inside a detached tmux. With
.BR --attach ,
connects immediately after adopting.
.TP
.BI "cs attach" " id-or-name"
Reconnect to a session. If the session is on the local machine,
attaches to the tmux session directly. If already inside tmux, uses
.B switch-client
to avoid nesting. If on a remote machine, executes
.BR ssh (1)
to the remote host and attaches there. Requires SSH key authentication for
remote sessions.
.PP
.RS
Sessions can be identified by ID prefix (like
.BR git (1)),
.B /rename
name (exact match), or title substring (case-insensitive). If the match is
ambiguous,
.B cs
lists all matches and exits.
.RE
.TP
.BI "cs kill" " id-or-name"
Terminate a tmux session.
.TP
.B cs resume
Interactive session picker using
.BR fzf (1).
Displays recent sessions from the current machine and launches
.B claude --resume
for the selected session.
.TP
.B cs last
Resume the most recent session on the current machine without a picker.
Equivalent to selecting the first item in
.BR "cs resume" .
.TP
.B cs status
Display live state of all active
.IR cs-*
tmux sessions on the current machine. Reads tmux directly; does not require
MongoDB. States are color-coded:
.RS
.TP
.B WORKING
(green) Claude is actively generating output.
.TP
.B WAITING
(yellow) Claude is waiting for user input or permission.
.TP
.B IDLE
(dim) Session is alive but has no recent activity.
.TP
.B DEAD
(red) tmux session no longer exists.
.RE
.TP
.BI "cs tag" " id-or-name label"
Apply a text label to a session. Tags are stored in MongoDB and displayed
in
.B cs list
output.
.TP
.BI "cs rm" " id-or-name"
Soft-delete a session. The record is marked with a
.I deleted_at
timestamp. It no longer appears in listings, queries, or sync, but can be
restored.
.TP
.BI "cs rm --undo" " id-or-name"
Restore a soft-deleted session.
.TP
.BI "cs prune" " [--days N] [--all]"
Bulk soft-delete sessions that have no
.B /rename
name and no tag. Default threshold is 30 days. With
.BR --all ,
prunes regardless of age. Named and tagged sessions are never pruned.
.TP
.BI "cs deleted" " [--local] [--host name]"
List soft-deleted sessions with deletion timestamps. Defaults to all hosts.
.TP
.BI "cs purge" " id-or-name [--yes]"
Hard delete a session. Removes the MongoDB record, JSONL file, and session
directory. Without
.BR --yes ,
shows what would be deleted. Must be run on the host where the session lives.
This is irreversible.
.TP
.BI "cs info" " id-or-name"
Display the full record for a single session, including session ID, machine,
project path, title, tag, state, message count, timestamps, tmux session name,
summary, and schema version.
.TP
.B cs hosts
List all hosts that have synced sessions, with session counts and last
seen timestamps.
.TP
.B cs update
Check for a new version on the remote server. If a newer version is available,
downloads the updated bundle and man page. If already up to date, prints the
current version and exits.
.TP
.BR "cs version" ", " "--version"
Print the current version and exit.
.TP
.BR "--help" ", " "-h"
Display usage summary and exit.
.SH SESSION TITLES
Sessions are automatically titled from the first human message in the
conversation. For example, if you started a session by typing "fix the nginx
config", that becomes the session title displayed in listings and the
dashboard. If a session name is set via
.B /rename
in Claude Code, that name takes priority and is also used as the tmux
session name.
.SH INSTALLATION
Install on any Linux host with:
.PP
.RS
.nf
curl -sSL https://git.bogometer.com/shartman/claude-session/-/raw/main/install-remote.sh | bash
.fi
.RE
.PP
Options (pass via
.BR "bash -s --" ):
.TP
.B --nocron
Skip automatic cron sync setup.
.TP
.B --noconfig
Skip config copy from source host.
.PP
Override the repo URL with
.BR CS_REPO_URL :
.PP
.RS
.nf
CS_REPO_URL=https://your-host/path curl ... | bash
.fi
.RE
.SH CONFIGURATION
Configuration is read from
.IR ~/.config/cs/config.json :
.PP
.RS
.nf
{
  "mongoUri": "mongodb://user:pass@host:27017/db?tls=true"
}
.fi
.RE
.PP
The file should be created with mode 0600 and the directory with mode 0700
to protect MongoDB credentials.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B NO_COLOR
If set, disables all ANSI color output. See
.IR https://no-color.org/ .
.TP
.B CS_REPO_URL
Override the default repository URL for
.B cs update
and
.BR install-remote.sh .
Useful for self-hosted GitLab or GitHub instances.
.TP
.B CS_CONFIG_HOST
SSH hostname to copy config from during install (default:
.IR cs ).
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.config/cs/config.json
MongoDB connection configuration.
.TP
.I ~/.claude/projects/<path-hash>/<session-id>.jsonl
Claude Code session files (read-only; cs never modifies these).
.TP
.I ~/.claude/projects/<path-hash>/<session-id>/session-memory/summary.md
Optional session summaries generated by Claude Code.
.TP
.I ~/.local/bin/cs
Default symlink location for the cs executable.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Error (missing config, MongoDB failure, unknown command, ambiguous prefix,
missing dependency).
.SH EXAMPLES
Import existing sessions and view the dashboard:
.PP
.RS
.nf
cs sync
cs
.fi
.RE
.PP
Launch a persistent session and reconnect later:
.PP
.RS
.nf
cs launch myproject "refactor the auth module"
cs attach a3f7
.fi
.RE
.PP
See what's running across all hosts:
.PP
.RS
.nf
cs list
cs hosts
.fi
.RE
.PP
Attach to a session running on a different machine:
.PP
.RS
.nf
cs list
cs attach 952d    # auto-SSH if remote
.fi
.RE
.PP
Tag and search:
.PP
.RS
.nf
cs tag 952d auth-refactor
cs list --project trading
.fi
.RE
.PP
Auto-sync on login (add to .bashrc):
.PP
.RS
.nf
cs sync --quiet &
.fi
.RE
.SH DEPENDENCIES
.TP
.BR bun (1)
JavaScript/TypeScript runtime. Auto-installed by the remote installer if missing.
.TP
.BR tmux (1)
Terminal multiplexer. Required for launch, attach, kill, and status commands.
.TP
.BR fzf (1)
Fuzzy finder. Required only for the
.B resume
command.
.TP
.BR ssh (1)
Secure shell. Required only for remote attach.
.TP
.B MongoDB 5+
Central database for session metadata. TLS and SCRAM-SHA-256 authentication.
.SH BUGS
Session state detection is heuristic and may misclassify states when Claude
Code changes its terminal output format.
.PP
Path hash decoding uses recursive reconstruction to handle dots and hyphens
in directory names. Deeply nested paths with many ambiguous separators may
fail to decode; such sessions are skipped during sync with a warning.
.SH AUTHORS
Shane Hartman and Claude Code.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR claude (1),
.BR tmux (1),
.BR fzf (1),
.BR ssh (1),
.BR mongosh (1)
